96
00:07:47,962 --> 00:07:52,783
There's no discussion of the council rules of the appointment power, if any, of the city council.

97
00:07:53,283 --> 00:08:02,725
You'll see that there's a section here on prohibitions, things that the city council should not or cannot act on.

98
00:08:05,275 --> 00:08:10,821
There's a discussion here or things that we recommend as council president, vice president, terms, things of that nature.

99
00:08:11,642 --> 00:08:18,189
And again, this is very broad as these are sort of an example, is the scope of authority of your legislative body.

100
00:08:21,172 --> 00:08:22,514
So we're gonna go down here.

101
00:08:24,184 --> 00:08:29,247
And again, as I said earlier, this is a discussion of the powers and authority of the executive branch.

102
00:08:29,588 --> 00:08:34,711
The existing charter does have a discussion about compensation, but again, that's very limited.

103
00:08:34,751 --> 00:08:39,674
And it also has a discussion about the mayor's appointing power.

104
00:08:41,495 --> 00:08:47,859
However, there's no discussion about what to do in terms of the absence of an executive and things of that nature.

105
00:08:49,060 --> 00:08:52,963
And Medford is a,

106
00:08:53,935 --> 00:09:05,160
is a mayor's city council form of government, there's not really a discussion about the mayor's authority to veto ordinances.

107
00:09:10,702 --> 00:09:19,606
So again, this is totally absent from the existing Medford City Charter, the discussion of the school committee, composition, compensation, structure,

108
00:09:21,536 --> 00:09:23,758
you know, chair, vice chair, things of that nature.

109
00:09:24,678 --> 00:09:31,123
So, again, if the city were to move forward with a newer modern charter, this would be an important thing to add.

110
00:09:35,826 --> 00:09:37,267
Administrative organization.

111
00:09:38,187 --> 00:09:40,409
The existing charter does not cover this.

112
00:09:42,151 --> 00:09:49,174
This is something that a person would have to go into the Massachusetts General to figure out how the city is structured.

113
00:09:49,514 --> 00:09:59,219
This is the section where you would define your city agencies and how they are, who they report to within the city government.

114
00:10:03,150 --> 00:10:07,532
Financial procedures, this is definitely part of a more modern city charter.

115
00:10:08,252 --> 00:10:29,943
This discusses how the city forms its operating budget and what's something that's becoming more and more important, you know, as government has become more complex over time, the city's capital improvement programs, how it spends money on its buildings, operations, land, things of that nature.

116
00:10:33,164 --> 00:10:38,332
There's a section here on, there's not a section of the current charter on elections.

117
00:10:40,896 --> 00:10:42,358
There's limited language on elections.

118
00:10:44,120 --> 00:10:49,008
And so this would sort of flesh this out, you know, more thoroughly.

119
00:10:55,982 --> 00:11:10,528
The current charter does not discuss citizen participation, particularly how citizens may be able to put items before the city council for vote and other measures of that nature.

120
00:11:13,468 --> 00:11:16,569
Another interesting one, again, that's not covered in existing charter is recall.

121
00:11:17,190 --> 00:11:18,690
Now this can be a contentious item.

122
00:11:18,710 --> 00:11:36,799
This is a committee formed by the mayor, but there are a lot, there are a number of communities that have a explanation of how citizens may move forward with a recall of elected officials if the community wants to sort of create those mechanisms.

123
00:11:41,700 --> 00:11:42,980
So these are general provisions.

124
00:11:43,701 --> 00:11:47,542
They cover things like how do we move forward with making charges, changes to the charter?

125
00:11:49,442 --> 00:11:56,464
And that charter balance of the record recommends on any charter is a periodic review of the charter.

126
00:11:56,724 --> 00:12:03,126
Is this particular structure keeping up to date with the best practices that we understand in public government?

127
00:12:10,421 --> 00:12:23,295
And again, because Medford is charter so limited, this is a provision, this is a section on transition.

128
00:12:24,036 --> 00:12:30,062
And essentially, you don't want to make a wholesale change to their charter and have to sort of

129
00:12:31,667 --> 00:12:48,737
automatically sort of implement those, those things, because there could be issues with that so the transition section is where the community determines what processes need to continue for how long, and how they transition to their new operation under the

130
00:12:49,669 --> 00:12:50,269
the new chart.

131
00:12:51,090 --> 00:12:58,913
It covers things like records, personnel, there can be some financial and administrative provisions, and things of that nature.

132
00:12:58,933 --> 00:13:04,095
And that really covers the memo, again, really briefly.

133
00:13:05,095 --> 00:13:13,699
One of the things that I did want to sort of highlight for the body is that one of the things that makes the

134
00:13:14,965 --> 00:13:19,309
sort of this exemplar model charter so helpful is the structure.

135
00:13:22,331 --> 00:13:30,999
You can keep all of the things that you currently have, again, they're very limited, but you could structure them in a way that's more readable, more understandable for your average citizen.

136
00:13:31,459 --> 00:13:38,305
In addition to sort of digging into some of these more substantive issues regarding actual municipal operation.

137
00:13:39,206 --> 00:13:41,067
So with that, I'll turn it back over to the committee.

138
00:13:41,928 --> 00:13:46,510
And I know that was very brief, but we'll open up to questions on any specific section.

139
00:13:49,191 --> 00:13:49,471
